        <descriptionSet>
            <description pref="false" dataDate="2016-06-01-14-46-21">
                <text>Steinlen’s poster advertises the reopening of a cabaret, the Chat Noir in Montmartre. Here the artist worked with several actors to present avant-garde shadow theater, which investigated the artistic and dramatic effects of silhouettes, starring R. Salis as the popular, improvisational narrator (“bonimenteur”) of each shadow performance.</text>
                <author>
                    <name refid="131347215" type="corporate" vocab="viaf">Visual Resources Association</name>
                    <role type="code" vocab="marcrelator">aut</role>
                </author>
            </description>
            <description pref="false" source="https://www.google.com/culturalinstitute/asset-viewer/tourn%C3%A9e-du-chat-noir-de-rodolphe-salis-tour-of-rodolphe-salis-chat-noir/BAEF9F-mDJvr0A" dataDate="2015-11-11-15-07-28">
                <text>Rodolph Salis established the Chat Noir (The Black Cat) as an artistic cabaret in Montmartre in 1881, and it soon became a popular gathering place for Montmartre's rising artists and writers. Beginning in 1892, Salis organized a company of performers from the cabaret to go on tour during the summer months. This large poster by Théophile Steinlen, one of the important artists whose career was launched at the Chat Noir, would have served as a kind of "coming attractions" announcement to be posted outside the venues hosting the tour.</text>
                <author>
                    <name refid="124291214" type="corporate" vocab="viaf">Google (Firm)</name>
                    <role type="code" vocab="marcrelator">aut</role>
                </author>
            </description>
        </descriptionSet>
